05221nam a22007575i 9780231550956DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20202020nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2019026955  a97802315509567 a10.7312/lave194702doi  a(DE-B1597)546065  a(OCoLC)1163878155  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aHC427.7b.L38 2020 4aHC427.7 7aHIS0080002bisacsh04a333.70951/090342231 aLavelle, Peter B., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Profits of Nature :bColonial Development and the Quest for Resources in Nineteenth-Century China /cPeter B. Lavelle. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource :b15 images, 9 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tConventions and Measures -- tIntroduction -- tI. Agriculture in an Era of Crisis -- tII. Geography in a Growing Empire -- tIII. Reclaiming the Land -- tIV. Promoting Profitable Crops -- tV. Water in a Fertile Frontier -- tVI. Sericulture in a Colonial Borderland -- tConclusion -- tAcknowledgments -- tChinese Terms -- tAbbreviations -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the nineteenth century, the Qing empire experienced a period of profound turmoil caused by an unprecedented conjunction of natural disasters, domestic rebellions, and foreign incursions. The imperial government responded to these calamities by introducing an array of new policies and institutions to bolster its power across its massive territories. In the process, Qing officials launched campaigns for natural resource development, seeking to take advantage of the unexploited lands, waters, and minerals of the empire’s vast hinterlands and borderlands.In this book, Peter B. Lavelle uses the life and career of Chinese statesman Zuo Zongtang (1812–1885) as a lens to explore the environmental history of this era. Although known for his pacification campaigns against rebel movements, Zuo was at the forefront of the nineteenth-century quest for natural resources. Influenced by his knowledge of nature, geography, and technology, he created government bureaus and oversaw state-funded projects to improve agriculture, sericulture, and other industries in territories across the empire. His work forged new patterns of colonial development in the Qing empire’s northwest borderlands, including Xinjiang, at a time when other empires were scrambling to secure access to resources around the globe. Weaving a narrative across the span of Zuo’s lifetime, The Profits of Nature offers a unique approach to understanding the dynamic relationship among social crises, colonialism, and the natural world during a critical juncture in Chinese history, between the high tide of imperial power in the eighteenth century and the challenges of modern state-building in the twentieth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aEconomic developmentzChinaxHistoryy19th century. 0aNatural resourcesxGovernment policyzChina. 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311071097708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020 Englishz978311070473008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020z9783110704525oZDB-23-DEG40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/lave1947040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231550956423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/c